    "",
    "## Recommendation",
    "",
    "Implement Option C (enhanced annual discount from 20% to 30%) immediately in Q1 2026. This is low-risk, easy to implement, and directly addresses the pricing+budget churn segment.",
    "",
    "Evaluate Option A (Starter tier at $15/seat/month) for Q3 2026. This requires more analysis on cannibalization risk and a clear feature scoping exercise.",
    "",
    "Evaluate Option D (AI Premium add-on) after AI features reach GA, likely Q3-Q4 2026. The pricing should be based on willingness-to-pay data collected during the GA rollout period."
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 28: Customer Health Score Framework ──
  createDocInFolder("Customer Health Score Framework", [
    "# Customer Health Score Framework",
    "",
    "Author: Priya Patel, Data Lead",
    "Date: December 2025",
    "Status: Proposed — pending review by Sarah Chen",
    "Related Documents: Churn Analysis Q3-Q4 2025, Product-Eng Sync Notes (Nov 15 and Dec 6), Churn Reduction Initiative Proposal",
    "",
    "## Overview",
    "",
    "The Customer Health Score is a composite score (0-100) predicting churn risk for each RavenStack account. It is built from quantitative analysis of our 500 accounts, 600 churn events, and approximately 2,000 support tickets across 2024-2025. The framework transforms reactive churn response (reacting after a customer leaves) into proactive churn prevention (intervening before a customer decides to leave).",
    "",
    "This framework was developed in response to the Q4 2025 churn spike (251 events, up 93% from Q3's 130 events). Sarah Chen requested a data-driven approach to identify at-risk accounts before they churn, based on a discussion at the November 15 Product-Eng Sync. The initial proof-of-concept (manual scoring of 10 at-risk Enterprise accounts in October) correctly identified 8 of 10 eventual outcomes, validating the approach.",
    "",
    "## Score Components",
    "",
    "The health score is the weighted sum of four component scores, each scaled 0-100:",
    "",
    "### Component 1: Feature Engagement (40% weight)",
    "",
    "Feature engagement is the strongest predictor of retention. Our analysis shows that accounts using 15+ features have 3x lower churn rate than accounts using fewer than 5 features.",
    "",
    "Sub-metrics:",
    "- Number of active features used in last 30 days (target: 15+)",
    "- Feature breadth score: ratio of features used to features available for the account's tier (Basic has access to ~25 features, Pro to ~35, Enterprise to all 40)",
    "- Key feature usage: accounts that use Dashboard Builder, Sprint Planning, and Integrations Hub together have the lowest churn rate of any segment",
    "- AI feature adoption: accounts using at least one AI beta feature (AI Search, AI Copilot, AI Summary, Smart Alerts, AI Agent Builder) have 25% lower churn, likely due to self-selection bias (engaged accounts try new features)",
    "- Red flag: fewer than 5 features used in last 30 days → score drops to 20/100 for this component",
    "",
    "Scoring formula: Base score = (features_used / features_available) x 100. Bonuses: +10 for using all 3 key features, +5 for using any AI feature. Penalty: -30 if fewer than 5 features used.",
    "",
    "### Component 2: Support Health (25% weight)",
    "",
    "Support interactions are a strong churn signal — especially when they go poorly. The critical finding from the November correlation analysis: accounts with 3+ urgent tickets in a quarter have 4x higher churn probability.",
    "",
    "Sub-metrics:",
    "- Number of tickets in last 90 days (more tickets = higher risk, unless CSAT is high)",
    "- Ticket priority distribution: proportion of urgent and high-priority tickets",
    "- CSAT trend: last 3 CSAT scores compared to account average. Declining CSAT is a risk signal.",
    "- Resolution time: how quickly the account's tickets are resolved relative to our 35.6-hour average",
    "- Critical threshold: 3+ urgent tickets in a quarter automatically sets this component to 15/100 (indicating high churn risk)",
    "",
    "Platform-wide benchmarks for reference: Average CSAT across all accounts is 3.97. Average resolution time is 35.6 hours. Total escalation rate is 4.75%.",
    "",
    "Scoring formula: Start at 80. -5 per ticket above 2 in last 90 days. -10 per urgent ticket above 1. -15 if CSAT trend is declining. +10 if CSAT is above 4.3 (September was 4.36, the best month).",
    "",
    "### Component 3: Usage Trend (20% weight)",
    "",
    "Usage trend captures momentum — whether an account is becoming more or less engaged over time.",
    "",
    "Sub-metrics:",
    "- Month-over-month usage count change (total feature uses this month vs last month)",
    "- Duration trend (average session duration this month vs last month)",
    "- Login frequency trend (daily active users this month vs last month)",
    "- Red flag: greater than 30% usage decline over 2 months → score drops to 10/100 for this component",
    "",
    "The August MRR dip ($648,426, down from $707,816 in July) was preceded by declining usage metrics in the 3 Enterprise accounts that paused. This validates usage trend as a leading indicator.",
    "",
    "Scoring formula: Start at 70. +20 if usage growing >10% MoM. +10 if flat (within 5%). -20 if declining 10-30%. -50 if declining >30%.",
    "",
    "### Component 4: Contract Health (15% weight)",
    "",
    "Contract health reflects the business relationship stability.",
    "",
    "Sub-metrics:",
    "- Days until renewal: accounts within 30 days of renewal are at higher risk",
    "- Billing frequency: annual billing customers have 40% lower churn (they have committed for 12 months, reducing impulsive cancellation)",
    "- Upgrade/downgrade history: accounts with recent downgrades (part of 218 total downgrade events) are at elevated risk",
    "- Auto-renew status: accounts with auto-renew disabled are significantly more likely to churn at renewal date",
    "",
    "Scoring formula: Start at 70. +20 for annual billing. -20 if renewal within 30 days. -15 for downgrade in last 90 days. +10 for auto-renew enabled.",
    "",
    "## Composite Score and Risk Tiers",
    "",
    "Composite score = (Feature Engagement x 0.40) + (Support Health x 0.25) + (Usage Trend x 0.20) + (Contract Health x 0.15)",
    "",
    "### Risk Tiers",
    "",
    "- Healthy (80-100): Engaged, growing usage, no support issues. Action: standard account management.",
    "- Watch (60-79): Some concerning signals. Action: proactive CSM outreach, feature adoption review.",
    "- At Risk (40-59): Multiple risk factors present. Action: immediate CSM intervention, executive sponsor engagement, custom retention plan.",
    "- Critical (0-39): Imminent churn risk. Action: immediate executive escalation, escalate to VP Product and Sales Lead.",
    "",
    "## Validation",
    "",
    "### Backtest Against Q4 2025 Churn",
    "",
    "We backtested the model against Q4 2025 churn (251 events) using data available 30 days before each churn event. Results:",
    "",
    "- The model correctly identified 78% (196 of 251) of churned accounts as 'At Risk' or 'Critical' 30 days before the churn date.",
    "- False positive rate: 15%. This means 15% of accounts flagged as 'At Risk' or 'Critical' did NOT churn in Q4. These false positives are actually useful — they represent accounts that were on the verge of churning but were retained (possibly due to natural factors or informal CSM intervention).",
    "- False negative rate: 22%. These are the 55 churned accounts that the model scored as 'Watch' or 'Healthy.' Analysis shows these are predominantly small Basic accounts with low engagement that churned suddenly (within 1 week of last login).",
    "",
    "### Proof-of-Concept Results",
    "",
    "In October 2025, we manually calculated health scores for 10 at-risk Enterprise accounts identified by the sales team. Results:",
    "- 3 accounts scored 'Critical' (0-39): all 3 churned in Q4",
    "- 5 accounts scored 'At Risk' (40-59): 3 churned, 2 were retained after CSM intervention",
    "- 2 accounts scored 'Watch' (60-79): both were retained (the sales team's risk assessment was overly conservative for these accounts)",
    "- Overall accuracy: 80% (8 of 10 correct predictions)",
    "",
    "## Churn Correlation Findings",
    "",
    "The correlation analysis (completed November 28, requested at the Nov 15 Product-Eng Sync) revealed these relationships:",
    "",
    "- Accounts with 3+ urgent tickets in Q4 had 4x higher churn rate (the strongest single predictor)",
    "- Accounts using fewer than 5 features churned at 3x the rate of accounts using 15+ features",
    "- The 'features' churn reason (53 events in Q4) correlates with low feature breadth — accounts that churned for 'features' used an average of 7 features, compared to 18 for retained accounts",
    "- The 'support' churn reason (41 events in Q4) correlates with high urgent ticket count and below-average CSAT scores",
    "- The 'budget' churn reason (47 events in Q4) does NOT correlate with engagement metrics — these accounts were often healthy from a usage perspective but faced external budget pressure. The health score model is weakest at predicting budget-driven churn.",
    "- The 'competitor' churn reason (33 events in Q4) correlates with accounts in DevTools (NimbusApp threat) and HealthTech (AcmeSaaS threat) verticals",
    "",
    "## Implementation Plan",
    "",
    "### Phase 1: Nightly Batch Scoring (January 2026)",
    "- Calculate health scores nightly for all 500 accounts using a scheduled job",
    "- Store scores in a dedicated database table with daily history for trend analysis",
    "- Generate a daily summary email to CS Lead (Emily Rodriguez) listing all accounts that changed risk tiers",
    "- Engineering effort: 2 sprints (Priya's data team + 1 backend engineer)",
    "",
    "### Phase 2: CSM Dashboard (February 2026)",
    "- Build a web dashboard for CSMs showing: account list sorted by risk tier, score trend over time, component breakdown, and recommended actions",
    "- Include drill-down views: which specific metrics are driving a low score for each account",
    "- Engineering effort: 3 sprints (frontend + backend + Priya's data team)",
    "",
    "### Phase 3: Automated Alerts (March 2026)",
    "- When an account drops below score 60 (from Watch to At Risk), automatically trigger:",
    "  - Slack notification to assigned CSM",
    "  - Email to account executive",
    "  - Entry in the at-risk account queue",
    "- When an account drops below score 40 (to Critical), additionally trigger:",
    "  - Email to VP Product (Sarah Chen) and Sales Lead (David Kim)",
    "  - Automatic QBR meeting scheduling prompt",
    "- Engineering effort: 1 sprint",
    "",
    "### Phase 4: Smart Alerts Integration (Q2 2026)",
    "- Connect the health score system to the Smart Alerts feature so that CSMs receive intelligent, prioritized notifications about account health changes",
    "- This phase depends on Smart Alerts reaching GA (target Q2 2026)",
    "- Engineering effort: 2 sprints"
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 29: Net Revenue Retention Analysis ──
  createDocInFolder("Net Revenue Retention Analysis", [
    "# Net Revenue Retention Analysis",
    "",
    "Author: Priya Patel, Data Lead",
    "Date: December 2025",
    "Status: Final — shared with executive team December 10",
    "Related Documents: MRR & Subscription Dashboard (2025), Churn Reduction Initiative Proposal, Customer Health Score Framework",
    "",
    "## Executive Summary",
    "",
    "Net Revenue Retention (NRR) measures how much revenue we retain and expand from existing customers, excluding new customer acquisition. It is the single most important metric for B2B SaaS companies because it indicates whether your product becomes more valuable to customers over time. An NRR above 100% means expansion outpaces contraction and churn; above 120% is considered excellent.",
    "",
    "Based on our analysis of subscription data (5,000 total subscriptions across 500 accounts), we estimate RavenStack's NRR at 115-125%. This is strong for a company at our stage but has room for improvement — the top quartile of B2B SaaS companies achieve 130-140% NRR.",
    "",
    "The analysis reveals a tale of two dynamics: vigorous expansion (529 upgrade events, strong seat growth within accounts) offset by concerning churn (600 events, 110 churned accounts). Improving NRR from ~120% to 130%+ requires reducing churn more than increasing expansion — the churn lever has higher impact.",
    "",
    "## Key Metrics",
    "",
    "### MRR Movement (Full Year 2025)",
    "",
    "- Starting MRR (January 2025): $273,186",
    "- Ending MRR (December 2025): $2,273,427",
    "- Absolute growth: $2,000,241 (8.3x increase)",
    "",
    "This growth combines new customer acquisition AND existing customer expansion. To calculate NRR, we need to isolate the existing customer component.",
    "",
    "### Subscription-Level Analysis",
    "",
    "Of 5,000 total subscriptions across 500 accounts:",
    "- 529 subscriptions (10.6%) have had an upgrade at some point (tier upgrade or seat addition)",
    "- 218 subscriptions (4.4%) have had a downgrade at some point (tier downgrade or seat reduction)",
    "- Upgrade:downgrade ratio = 2.4:1 (healthy — means expansion significantly outpaces contraction)",
    "",
